opened_prs.title: Add wss support
opened_prs.body: Add native-tls to `tokio-tungstenite` to support wss

opened_prs.title: feat: add TLS support in Proxy client
opened_prs.body:
Adds TLS compatibility to client in the proxy. 

This is important as the JWT can be sniffed out of the headers in non `https` connections with the builder. These changes are backwards compatible with `http`, but now allow `rollup-boost` to connect to the builder over the auth API in the proxy through TLS.

repo.name: rollup-boost
repo.description: Proxy server for the Ethereum Engine API

opened_prs.title: Add circuit breaker
opened_prs.body:
Resolves https://github.com/flashbots/rollup-boost/issues/91

Notes:
- Only stops all engine calls to the builder (not forwarded calls - can add as a follow up if needed)
- Default to 5 slots 
- Updated README
- Adds test for circuit breaker condition

opened_prs.title: Add build on each commit to main
Add support for multiple builder and block selection

opened_issues.title: Record the backend with the latency of remote calls
opened_issues.body:
Right now the latency metrics are over how long it takes rollup boost to process each operation. It would be more interesting to know how long each backend takes to process each engine API operation.

We can see how long rollup boost takes via metrics on op-node.

opened_issues.title: Make FCU vs forkChoiceUpdated consistent in metrics
opened_issues.body: The count uses FCU, the latency uses fork_choice_updated

opened_issues.title: First block in integration tests is not deterministic
opened_issues.body: The way we run the integration tests makes non-deterministic who is the builder for the first block. We have to figure out why is that happening and either address it in Rollup-boost or in the integration framework itself.

opened_issues.title: Circuit Breaker
opened_issues.body: Similar to the idea of a circuit breaker for mev-boost on L1, rollup boost should auto shut off a block builder if multiple invalid payloads come from that block builder. TBD what turning the builder back on looks like. https://hackmd.io/@ralexstokes/BJn9N6Thc

opened_issues.title: Block Builder Creator Log or Metric
opened_issues.body: Rollup Boost should log or provide a metric for who built a block that it received. Discretion is available to the developer for whether this is a log or a metric.

opened_issues.title: Document how debug API + dry run mode work
opened_issues.body: Dry run builder mode and debug RPC were introduced in https://github.com/flashbots/rollup-boost/commit/22b0846866a5b5758b86c95f9da58f74e6cfe082 and we need documentation for how to use this mode and API.

opened_issues.title: Remove PayloadID field in FCU request if not doing block building
opened_issues.body:
Whenever Rollup-boost receives a FCU update without payload attributes it logs this message when it calls the builder
```
2025-02-09T10:16:04.643822Z  INFO rollup_boost::server: called fork_choice_updated_v3 to builder with payload attributes url=http://localhost:8553/ payload_status=VALID payload_id=""
```
It is confusing to have `payload_id=""` since this call does not generate a payload id. We should print a different log in that case.

closed_prs.title: Remove reth deps
closed_prs.body: This PR removes the three Reth dependencies we had since we can replace them with dependencies from alloy and copying a couple of simple functions from Reth.

closed_prs.title: Add a proxy in between Rollup-boost + Rbuilder and simulate latencies
closed_prs.body:
This PR adds a proxy in between Rollup-boost and the builder and adds two tests:
- One that simulates latency between Rollup-boost and the builder.
- One that changes the state root from the payload returned by the builder. Rollup-boost has to detect it and return the L2 block.

closed_prs.title: Cleanup Integration + builder down integration test
closed_prs.body:
This PR does several things:
- It cleans up a little bit of the integration framework (introduces functions to start/stop/restart the services).
- It connects through P2P the EL and Builder instances of the integration test harness.
- It introduces a new test that checks that the builder can be stopped, rollup-boost does not fail and once the builder gets restarted the system goes back to normal.

Make the builder optional
closed_issues.body: If the builder is not explicitly set, the rollup-boost just defaults to relaying the op-node requests.
